-{"id":"bd-2go9","title":"charmed_log: Document and optimize backtrace overhead in caller reporting","description":"# Task: Address Backtrace Performance Overhead

## Problem Statement
When report_caller is enabled, every log call captures a full stack backtrace:

```rust
// Line 308
let bt = Backtrace::new();
let frames: Vec<_> = bt.frames().iter().collect();
```

Backtrace capture is extremely expensive - 100-1000x slower than normal logging.
This can turn a 100ns log call into 100μs+ operation.

## Impact Analysis
- **Accidental enablement**: Developer enables for debugging, forgets to disable
- **Production slowdown**: Application throughput tanks unexpectedly
- **No warning**: User has no indication of the performance cost
- **Memory pressure**: Each backtrace allocates significant memory

## Solution Design

### 1. Add Performance Warning in Documentation
```rust
/// Enable caller information in log output.
///
/// # Performance Warning
/// 
/// When enabled, this captures a full stack backtrace on EVERY log call,
/// which is approximately 100-1000x slower than normal logging.
/// 
/// **Only enable during active debugging sessions.**
/// **Do NOT enable in production.**
///
/// Typical overhead: ~100μs per log call vs ~100ns without.
pub fn with_caller(self) -> Self { ... }
```

### 2. Add Runtime Warning (Optional)
On first log with caller reporting enabled, print warning:
```
[charmed_log] WARNING: Caller reporting enabled - expect 100x performance overhead
```

### 3. Consider Lazy/Cached Backtrace (Future Enhancement)
Could implement lazy capture that only resolves symbols when actually needed,
but this is complex and may not be worth the effort.

### 4. Add Benchmark
Create benchmark showing the performance difference:
```rust
#[bench]
fn bench_log_without_caller(b: &mut Bencher) { ... }

#[bench]  
fn bench_log_with_caller(b: &mut Bencher) { ... }
```

## Implementation Steps
1. Add detailed performance warning to with_caller() docs
2. Add runtime warning on first use (with flag to disable)
3. Add benchmarks comparing with/without caller reporting
4. Update README with performance considerations section

## Testing Strategy
- Verify warning appears on first log with caller enabled
- Benchmark to establish baseline and document actual overhead
- Test that warning can be suppressed

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Documentation warns about 100x+ overhead
- [ ] Optional runtime warning on first use
- [ ] Benchmarks added to track performance
- [ ] README updated with performance section","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-01-28T02:16:19.783279254Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-01-28T02:16:29.297290484Z","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["charmed_log","documentation","performance"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-2go9","depends_on_id":"bd-1bja","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-01-28T02:16:29.297259867Z","created_by":"ubuntu"},{"issue_id":"bd-2go9","depends_on_id":"bd-3ju1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-01-28T02:16:19.799318568Z","created_by":"ubuntu"}]}
